04585nam a22007215i 9780823238163DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232381637 a10.1515/97808232381632doi  a(DE-B1597)555418  a(OCoLC)1099151403  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0180002bisacsh1 aHorner, Robyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRethinking God as Gift :bMarion, Derrida, and the Limits of Phenomenology /cRobyn Horner. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Problem of the Gift -- t2 Husserl and Heidegger -- t3 Levinas -- t4 Refiguring Givenness -- t5 Being Given -- t6 The Limits of Phenomenology -- t7 Rethinking the Gift I -- t8 Rethinking the Gift II -- tEpilogue: Naming the Gift, Giving a Name, Rethinking God As Gift -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRethinking God as Gift is situated at the intersection of philosophy, critical theory and theology. The first sustained study of the work of Jean-Luc Marion in English, it offers a unique perspective on contemporary questions and their theological relevance. Taking its point of departure from the problem of the gift as articulated by Jacques Derrida, who argues that the conditions of possibility of the gift are also its conditions of impossibility, Horner pursues a series of questions concerning the nature of thought, the viability of phenomenology, and, most urgently, the possibility of grace. For Marion, phenomenology, as the thought of the given, offers a path for philosophy to proceed without being implicated in metaphysics. His retrieval of several important insights of Edmund Husserl, along with his reading of Martin Heidegger and Emmanuel Lévinas, enables him to work out a phenomenology where even “impossible” phenomena such as revelation and the gift might be examined. In this important confrontation between Marion and Derrida issues vital to the negotiation of postmodern concerns in philosophy and theology emerge with vigour. The careful elucidation of those issues in an interdisciplinary context, and the snapshot it provides of the state of contemporary debate, make Rethinking God as Gift an important contribution to theological and philosophical discussion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aGiftsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPhenomenological theology. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aReligion. 4aTheology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322121940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823238163?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823238163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823238163/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK